<TITLE> No politics, please: new Baitul Mukarram Khatib </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 2 (bdnews24.com)  The newly appointed Khatib of Baitul Mukarram says he is against any political activities in the national mosque. "We do not want the peaceful environment of the mosque hampered by any political activities," Maulana Muhammad Salahuddin, who was appointed Khatib on Thursday, told bdnews24.com on Friday. "So we'll advise all to refrain from any kind of political activities in and around the mosque." Salahuddin is scheduled to take over on Sunday. "No-one expects the peaceful environment of a sacred place like mosque to be disturbed. We'll make efforts to maintain that peaceful environment," Salahuddin said. The new Khatib said he would see to it that the imams did not deliver political statement that "could cause instability". "The mosque is a place for religious discussions. Any political discussion here could cause instability. We'll try to not to let it happen," he said. About his responsibility as Khatib a person who delivers the sermon during the Friday or Eid prayers Salahuddin said he would spread the peaceful message of Islam. The Islamic Foundation on Thursday issued him his appointment letter under orders from the religious affairs ministry, public relations officer of the foundation Touhidul Islam said. Salahuddin, former principal of Madrasa-i-Aliah, Dhaka, had been the Khatib of Gausul Azam Mosque at Mohakhali. Mufti Muhammad Nuruddin had been acting as the Khatib of Baitul Mokarram since former Khatib Maulana Ubaidul Haque's death. bdnew
